  "prompt": "What is the highest temperature ever recorded in the universe?",
  "response": "The highest temperature ever recorded in the universe isn't something we observe directly. Instead, we talk about the highest temperature achieved *experimentally*, which is what scientists believe existed a tiny fraction of a second after the Big Bang. That temperature is estimated to be **5.5 trillion degrees Celsius (9.9 trillion degrees Fahrenheit)**.\n\nThis incredibly hot state was achieved at the **Relativistic Heavy Ion Collider (RHIC)** at Brookhaven National Laboratory and later at the **Large Hadron Collider (LHC)** at CERN. They smash heavy ions, like gold or lead, together at near-light speed, creating a quark-gluon plasma. This plasma is thought to be the state of matter that existed in the very early universe.\n\nTherefore, to clarify:\n\n*   **Not directly \"recorded\" in the sense of an observed natural phenomenon:** This isn't like measuring the hottest day in the Sahara.\n*   **Experimentally achieved and theoretically linked to the early universe:** Scientists recreated conditions thought to be similar to those shortly after the Big Bang.\n*   **Estimate:** The 5.5 trillion degrees Celsius is based on calculations and models, not a direct temperature reading in the conventional sense.\n\nSo, while we can't point to a single spot in the cosmos and say \"that's the hottest place ever,\" the quark-gluon plasma experiments give us the best estimate of the highest temperature that likely existed in the early universe.\n",
